---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import ThemeToggle from "../../components/ThemeToggle.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
import { posts } from "../../data/posts";
import { site } from "../../data/site";

const post = posts.find((p) => p.slug === "inattentional-blindness")!;
const canonical = `${site.url}blog/${post.slug}/`;
---

<BaseLayout
  title={`${post.title} · Aasim Sani`}
  description={post.description}
  ogType="article"
  ogTitle={post.title}
  ogImage={`${site.url.replace(/\/$/, "")}${post.ogImage}`}
  canonical={canonical}
  publishedTime={post.published}
>
  <ThemeToggle />
  <div class="read-progress" aria-hidden="true"><span></span></div>

  <main class="post">
    <header class="post-header">
      <a class="home-link" href="/blog/">&larr; Writing</a>
      <p class="kicker">Inattentional blindness &middot; root-caused</p>
      <h1>Your startup isn&rsquo;t slow. It&rsquo;s blind.</h1>
      <p class="dek">
        Why good engineers miss obvious things, why it compounds into slow
        roadmaps, and the two-person structure that catches what one pair of
        eyes can&rsquo;t.
      </p>
      <div class="byline">
        <span><b>Aasim Sani</b></span>
        <span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span>
        <span>{post.displayDate}</span>
        <span aria-hidden="true">&middot;</span>
        <span>{post.readingTime}</span>
      </div>
    </header>

    <!-- ============ 0 · The demo ============ -->
    <section id="demo">
      <p class="lede">
        Before I argue anything, review a pull request with me.
      </p>
      <p>
        A teammate renamed <code>user_items</code> to <code>digest_items</code>
        in the weekly-email module. Your job is the usual one: confirm the
        rename is complete. There are <b>six occurrences</b> of the old name.
        Check every one. Take it as seriously as you would at work &mdash;
        there&rsquo;s a question at the end.
      </p>

      <figure class="diff" aria-label="A code diff renaming user_items to digest_items">
        <div class="diff-title"><span class="diff-file">notifications/digest.py</span><span class="diff-stat">+6 &minus;7</span></div>
        <pre><code><span class="dl ctx">  def send_weekly_digest(user, stories):</span>
<span class="dl del">-     user_items = []</span>
<span class="dl add">+     digest_items = []</span>
<span class="dl ctx">      for story in stories:</span>
<span class="dl del">-         user_items.append(render_card(story))</span>
<span class="dl add">+         digest_items.append(render_card(story))</span>
<span class="dl ctx">      if user.language != "en":</span>
<span class="dl del">-         user_items = translate(user_items, user.language)</span>
<span class="dl add">+         digest_items = translate(digest_items, user.language)</span>
<span class="dl del">-     if user.unsubscribed:</span>
<span class="dl del">-         return None</span>
<span class="dl ctx">      subject = pick_subject(stories)</span>
<span class="dl del">-     mailer.queue(user.email, subject, user_items)</span>
<span class="dl add">+     mailer.queue(user.email, subject, digest_items)</span>
<span class="dl ctx">      audit_log.record(user.id, subject)</span>
<span class="dl del">-     return DigestReceipt(user_items)</span>
<span class="dl add">+     return DigestReceipt(digest_items)</span></code></pre>
      </figure>

      <details class="reveal">
        <summary>Lock in your answer &mdash; was the rename complete?</summary>
        <div class="reveal-body">
          <p>
            <b>Yes. All six occurrences were renamed, perfectly.</b> And if
            that&rsquo;s what you checked, you almost certainly sailed past the
            two lines in the middle that have nothing to do with the rename:
          </p>
          <pre class="reveal-snippet"><code>-     if user.unsubscribed:
-         return None</code></pre>
          <p>
            This diff also <b>deletes the unsubscribe guard</b>. Every person
            who opted out starts getting emailed again. It isn&rsquo;t hidden
            &mdash; it&rsquo;s in plain sight, unpaired, in the middle of the
            diff. But your task was &ldquo;find <code>user_items</code> &rarr;
            <code>digest_items</code> pairs,&rdquo; so that&rsquo;s the
            template your attention ran, and an off-template deletion
            didn&rsquo;t register.
          </p>
          <p>
            If you caught it: notice that you were primed &mdash; you knew this
            essay was going to test you, and you still felt the pull to stop
            looking the moment the sixth rename checked out.
          </p>
          <p>
            I didn&rsquo;t invent this failure shape. A guard clause silently
            lost inside an unrelated change &mdash; shipped, and caught by the
            people it was protecting &mdash; is a failure shape I&rsquo;ve
            root-caused more than once. It has a name, and it&rsquo;s quietly
            taxing your roadmap.
          </p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 1 · The science ============ -->
    <section id="science">
      <p class="section-label">01 &middot; The gorilla, twice</p>
      <h2>Looking is not seeing</h2>
      <p>
        In 1999, Daniel Simons and Christopher Chabris asked people to watch a
        video of two teams passing basketballs and count the passes made by the
        team in white. Halfway through, a person in a gorilla suit walks into
        the middle of the frame, thumps their chest, and walks off. It&rsquo;s
        on screen for nine seconds. <b>About half the viewers never see
        it.</b><sup><a href="#src-1">1</a></sup>
      </p>
      <p>
        The follow-up is the one that should worry engineers. In 2013, Trafton
        Drew and colleagues embedded a gorilla &mdash; about 48 times the size
        of a typical lung nodule &mdash; into CT scans and asked 24 expert
        radiologists to hunt for nodules. <b>Twenty of the 24 never saw
        it.</b> Eye-tracking showed that most of the radiologists who missed it
        looked <em>directly at it</em>.<sup><a href="#src-2">2</a></sup>
      </p>

      <figure class="chart" role="img" aria-label="Bar chart: about 50% of untrained viewers miss the gorilla in the basketball video; 83% of expert radiologists missed it in CT scans.">
        <figcaption class="chart-title">Who misses the gorilla?</figcaption>
        <svg viewBox="0 0 640 190" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg">
          <g font-family="var(--font-mono)" font-size="13">
            <!-- row 1 -->
            <text x="0" y="34" fill="var(--color-ink-soft)">Untrained viewers, basketball video</text>
            <rect x="0" y="44" width="560" height="14" rx="4" fill="var(--color-fog)"></rect>
            <rect x="0" y="44" width="280" height="14" rx="4" fill="var(--color-terracotta)"></rect>
            <text x="292" y="56" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-weight="500">~50% miss it</text>
            <!-- row 2 -->
            <text x="0" y="104" fill="var(--color-ink-soft)">Expert radiologists, CT lung scans</text>
            <rect x="0" y="114" width="560" height="14" rx="4" fill="var(--color-fog)"></rect>
            <rect x="0" y="114" width="465" height="14" rx="4" fill="var(--color-terracotta)"></rect>
            <text x="477" y="126" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-weight="500">83%</text>
            <!-- annotation -->
            <text x="0" y="172" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="12.5">Most radiologists who missed it looked directly at it (eye-tracking).</text>
          </g>
        </svg>
      </figure>

      <p>Two things make this finding brutal:</p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <b>Expertise doesn&rsquo;t protect you.</b> These were trained
          specialists doing exactly the inspection they do every day. Their
          miss rate was <em>higher</em> than the public&rsquo;s &mdash; not
          because they were worse, but because their attention was more
          disciplined. They were running a tighter template.
        </li>
        <li>
          <b>Looking is not seeing.</b> The eye-tracking data kills the
          comforting story that misses come from laziness. You can point your
          eyes at the bug and not see the bug.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        The mechanism is well studied. Attention is a finite budget, not a
        virtue: the harder the primary task, the less capacity remains for
        anything else &mdash; including things that are large, unusual, and
        directly in view.<sup><a href="#src-3">3</a></sup> Under high
        perceptual load, unexpected things don&rsquo;t register dimly.
        They don&rsquo;t register at all. The effect shows up wherever
        inspection work meets pressure: one <i>Safety Science</i> study of 53
        construction supervisors attributed roughly <b>half of their missed
        hazards</b> to inattentional blindness &mdash; not ignorance, not
        negligence, attention.<sup><a href="#src-4">4</a></sup>
      </p>
      <p>
        Daniel Kahneman spends the opening of <i>Thinking, Fast and Slow</i>
        on this exact experiment and lands on nine words that should be
        stenciled onto every code-review tool: <b>&ldquo;we can be blind to
        the obvious, and we are also blind to our
        blindness.&rdquo;</b><sup><a href="#src-7">7</a></sup> His frame
        explains why. Fast, automatic System&nbsp;1 does the
        pattern-matching; slow, deliberate System&nbsp;2 does the verifying
        &mdash; and System&nbsp;2 is famously lazy, rationing itself hardest
        exactly when load is highest. A reviewer skimming a diff at
        5&nbsp;p.m. isn&rsquo;t verifying. They&rsquo;re pattern-matching for
        the shapes they expect &mdash; and, Kahneman again, <em>what you see
        is all there is</em>: System&nbsp;1 builds a coherent story from
        what&rsquo;s in front of it and never, ever flags what&rsquo;s
        missing.
      </p>

      <figure class="load-demo" aria-label="Interactive demo: increasing cognitive load narrows what you can see in a code file.">
        <figcaption class="chart-title">Attention is a budget &mdash; feel it</figcaption>
        <div class="load-controls">
          <label for="loadSlider">Deadline pressure</label>
          <input id="loadSlider" type="range" min="0" max="100" value="55" />
          <span class="load-readout" id="loadReadout">55%</span>
        </div>
        <pre class="load-code" id="loadCode" style="--load:0.55"><code><span class="cl" style="--d:4"># worker liveness check &mdash; restarts stuck workers</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:3">RECENT = timedelta(minutes=10)</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:2"></span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:1">def health_check(worker):</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:0">    last = worker.last_completed_activity()</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:0">    if now() - last &gt; RECENT:</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:0">        worker.kill()  # assume stuck, force restart</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:1">    </span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:2"># NOTE: nightly reconciliation activities legitimately</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:3"># run 2&ndash;6 hours with no intermediate completions.</span>
<span class="cl" style="--d:4"># They will look "stuck" to any 10-minute heuristic.</span></code></pre>
        <p class="load-caption">
          The lines you&rsquo;re editing stay sharp. The comment that
          invalidates your whole approach lives in the periphery &mdash; and
          the periphery is what load deletes first. Load doesn&rsquo;t make
          you sloppier. It makes you <em>narrower</em>.
        </p>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Now describe a startup engineer&rsquo;s day in these terms: a
        high-load primary task (ship the feature), time pressure, constant
        context switching, and a strong prior about what the code is supposed
        to do. A sprint is a selective-attention test that runs eight hours a
        day. The gorilla is whatever your task template doesn&rsquo;t match.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 2 · Case files ============ -->
    <section id="cases">
      <p class="section-label">02 &middot; The case files</p>
      <h2>Root-causing a decade of misses</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        I&rsquo;ve been root-causing engineering incidents for a decade: at
        Orai (AI speech coaching, 1M+ users), at CopyCat (Figma-to-code, 20k+
        developers), and across teams I&rsquo;ve worked with and compared
        notes with since. The files below are anonymized composites &mdash;
        every mechanism is real; the identifying details are deliberately
        altered so none of them trace to any one company. Different products,
        different stacks, different people. Same failure signature.
      </p>
      <p>
        None of these were incompetence. Every one is an attention system
        running exactly as designed &mdash; pointed at the wrong thing. For
        each file, ask yourself the question before opening the verdict:
        <em>who was positioned to see this one coming?</em>
      </p>

      <div class="case-grid">
        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 01</span>
            <span class="case-name">The rename that deleted a business rule</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              An update to how an integration wrote one configuration setting
              was reviewed for what it was <em>supposed</em> to do &mdash;
              write the new setting. What nobody saw: as a side effect, it
              silently wiped an adjacent set of pricing rules. Documents went
              out the door computed without them.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>the intended change</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>the unintended one, in the same diff</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>the customer</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A technical peer.</b> The author reviewed their own diff and saw what they meant, not what it did. A second engineer asking &ldquo;what else does this change?&rdquo; &mdash; rather than &ldquo;does it do the thing?&rdquo; &mdash; is the counter-template. This is the demo you just did, in production.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 02</span>
            <span class="case-name">The pipeline that failed silently for weeks</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              A refactor changed a file-naming convention inside a data
              ingestion pipeline. Nothing errored. The pipeline simply stopped
              ingesting one class of records &mdash; tens of thousands of them,
              for weeks &mdash; until downstream numbers looked absurd enough
              that a human went digging. Reports built on the missing data had
              quietly gone to zero, and nothing inside the building noticed.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>errors and red dashboards</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>absence &mdash; the records that never arrived</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>a human squinting at a suspicious total</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A standard holder.</b> No engineer&rsquo;s alert fires on silence they didn&rsquo;t predict. But anyone who owned the standard &ldquo;this account produces roughly this volume every month&rdquo; would have flagged a zero month in minutes. Monitoring watches what we expect to break; standards watch what must stay true.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 03</span>
            <span class="case-name">The regression QA couldn&rsquo;t see</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              A release broke the app &mdash; but only for logged-out users.
              Every internal tester, every QA pass, every Friday demo: logged
              in. The happy path was tested to death; the path nobody inside
              the building inhabits was invisible until people outside the
              building hit it.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>the path we demo</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>the path we never personally walk</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>strangers</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A technical peer</b> &mdash; barely. A reviewer or QA partner whose checklist includes the unglamorous states (logged out, empty, erroring) is attention redundancy for exactly the paths the author&rsquo;s excitement skips. Demo pressure aims everyone&rsquo;s budget at the same pixels.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 04</span>
            <span class="case-name">The invisible character</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              A production crash in a backend rules engine traced, after hours
              of debugging, to <code>"PREMIUM SUPPORT&nbsp;"</code> failing to
              match <code>"PREMIUM SUPPORT"</code>. A trailing space in one
              reference table. Engineers stared <em>at the string</em>
              repeatedly and saw equality, because their attention model said
              these strings are equal.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>the logic around the data</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>a literally invisible character</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>whoever finally diffed the bytes</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A technical peer</b> &mdash; but honestly, this one is the radiology study wearing a costume. You can look straight at a defect and not see it. The lesson isn&rsquo;t &ldquo;look harder&rdquo;; it&rsquo;s that fresh eyes run a different template, and different templates see different gorillas.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 05</span>
            <span class="case-name">Right code, wrong &ldquo;correct&rdquo;</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              A metering bug was found and fixed &mdash; properly. Affected
              historical usage was recalculated &mdash; carefully.
              Engineering&rsquo;s definition of done: the numbers are now
              mathematically right. Finance&rsquo;s definition: the books must
              match what customers were <em>actually charged</em>. The
              recalculated numbers flowed into the books, and now the two
              disagreed. Nobody was wrong inside their own frame. The frames
              were never held up against each other.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>making the math right</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>what &ldquo;right&rdquo; means downstream</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>the finance team, at close</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A standard holder.</b> No code review can catch correct code aimed at the wrong definition of correct. The person who owns the standard &mdash; &ldquo;the books match the charges, always&rdquo; &mdash; would have caught this in the one-sentence plan, before a line was written.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 06</span>
            <span class="case-name">Nobody asked what else was running</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              Mid-incident, the team discovered the customer had a second tool
              doing the same job running alongside theirs the entire time
              &mdash; with all the double-processing risk that implies. No
              engineer&rsquo;s checklist contained the question, because it
              isn&rsquo;t an engineering question. It&rsquo;s a
              know-the-customer&rsquo;s-world question, and nobody whose job
              that was had been in the loop.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>our system&rsquo;s behavior</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>the customer&rsquo;s world around it</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>incident responders, too late</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A standard holder.</b> Domain context is a form of attention. The non-technical partner &mdash; ops, sales, customer success &mdash; carries a map of the customer&rsquo;s reality that engineering&rsquo;s task template will never include.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 07</span>
            <span class="case-name">The same gorilla, caught once, missed once</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              At Orai we switched speech-transcription vendors. The first time,
              a teammate testing the output that same day noticed a quality
              metric had flatlined at zero &mdash; the new vendor didn&rsquo;t
              return a confidence field the old one did. Rolled back within
              hours. Two months later we switched again, and this time nobody
              enumerated what else the old vendor had been quietly providing.
              Punctuation, it turned out &mdash; which fed our pause and
              sentence-length detection. Users started getting told their
              sentences were &ldquo;too long&rdquo; no matter how they spoke.
              We found out from a cluster of angry app-store reviews.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>the migration going green</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>the fields the old vendor supplied for free</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>hours of fresh eyes once; app-store reviews the other time</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A technical peer</b> &mdash; and this pair of incidents is the cleanest A/B test I have. Same team, same integration, same class of bug. The switch with a second attention system pointed at the output was caught in hours. The switch without one was caught by customers. The variable wasn&rsquo;t skill. It was coverage.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>

        <details class="case">
          <summary>
            <span class="case-no">File 08</span>
            <span class="case-name">The demo looked right for a year</span>
          </summary>
          <div class="case-body">
            <p>
              At CopyCat we generated working code from Figma designs. When
              someone finally ran a dedicated fidelity audit &mdash; looking
              for gaps instead of confirming the demo &mdash; they found a
              missing <code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;</code> that had been silently
              dropping every preview into the browser&rsquo;s fallback
              stylesheet, text wrapping a few pixels off on real designs, and
              an old positioning &ldquo;fix&rdquo; that had solved the one
              visible bad case while quietly mis-positioning elements on
              designs we never tested. The engineer&rsquo;s own explanation was
              the honest one: they hadn&rsquo;t known the CSS precedence rule
              &mdash; the fix was written for the failure in front of them,
              &ldquo;nothing specific to a failure condition.&rdquo; All of it
              latent since implementation. All of it invisible, because our
              test designs never exercised it.
            </p>
            <dl class="case-facts">
              <div><dt>Staring at</dt><dd>the demo files we always tested with</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Invisible</dt><dd>everything those files didn&rsquo;t exercise</dd></div>
              <div><dt>Seen first by</dt><dd>the first person who hunted gaps, not confirmation</dd></div>
            </dl>
            <details class="verdict"><summary>Who was positioned to catch it?</summary>
              <p><b>A standard holder.</b> Engineering kept confirming that the code ran. It took someone whose standard was &ldquo;pixel-true to the design&rdquo; &mdash; a designer&rsquo;s definition of correct, not a compiler&rsquo;s &mdash; to see what had been wrong the whole time. Different standard, different gorilla.</p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </details>
      </div>

      <p>
        I could keep going &mdash; and the quieter, internal misses tell the
        same story with lower stakes. A bulk backfill that burned an entire
        third-party API quota in one run, because nobody had modeled what
        &ldquo;batch&rdquo; does to a service that had only ever been called
        one row at a time (CI caught it; no customer ever knew). A CopyCat
        build server that died of quietly accumulating disk exhaustion &mdash;
        on the morning of an investor call. An Orai feature that sat silently
        dead for three or four months until a customer&rsquo;s email told us.
        Once you have the lens, you stop seeing bad luck and start seeing one
        mechanism, over and over.
      </p>
      <p>
        And lest this sound like a junior-engineer problem: in one of these
        files, the person who received a teammate&rsquo;s explicit warning
        about a crash-causing null &mdash; and waved it off, heads-down on a
        migration &mdash; was a founder. The apology arrived the next morning,
        with the crash. Seniority doesn&rsquo;t buy you out of the attention
        budget; it usually means you&rsquo;re carrying more load, which makes
        you blinder.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 3 · Two channels ============ -->
    <section id="channels">
      <p class="section-label">03 &middot; The taxonomy</p>
      <h2>Two channels of blindness</h2>
      <p>
        Sort every case file above &mdash; and every escaped defect
        you&rsquo;ve root-caused &mdash; and they ride one of two channels:
      </p>

      <figure class="diagram" role="img" aria-label="Diagram: a developer at full attentional load produces misses through two channels — technical (code diverges from intent) and alignment (intent diverges from need) — both shipping and being found late.">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 300" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="var(--font-mono)">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="7" markerHeight="7" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M 0 1 L 9 5 L 0 9" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-stone)" stroke-width="1.6"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- developer node -->
          <rect x="10" y="110" width="180" height="80" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="100" y="143" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="13.5" font-weight="500">One developer</text>
          <text x="100" y="163" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11.5">at full attentional load</text>
          <!-- channel 1 -->
          <line x1="190" y1="130" x2="268" y2="72" stroke="var(--color-stone)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
          <rect x="272" y="30" width="230" height="84" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="387" y="58" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-terracotta)" font-size="11" letter-spacing="1.5">CHANNEL 1 · TECHNICAL</text>
          <text x="387" y="80" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="13">code &ne; intent</text>
          <text x="387" y="99" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">you can&rsquo;t proofread your own model</text>
          <!-- channel 2 -->
          <line x1="190" y1="170" x2="268" y2="228" stroke="var(--color-stone)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
          <rect x="272" y="186" width="230" height="84" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-sage-dim)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="387" y="214" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-sage-dim)" font-size="11" letter-spacing="1.5">CHANNEL 2 · ALIGNMENT</text>
          <text x="387" y="236" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="13">intent &ne; need</text>
          <text x="387" y="255" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">correctly built, correctly wrong</text>
          <!-- converge -->
          <line x1="502" y1="72" x2="580" y2="132" stroke="var(--color-stone)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
          <line x1="502" y1="228" x2="580" y2="168" stroke="var(--color-stone)" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#arr)"/>
          <rect x="584" y="118" width="88" height="64" rx="10" fill="var(--color-terracotta)" opacity="0.14"/>
          <rect x="584" y="118" width="88" height="64" rx="10" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="628" y="145" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="12" font-weight="500">shipped,</text>
          <text x="628" y="163" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="12" font-weight="500">found late</text>
        </svg>
      </figure>

      <p>
        <b>Channel 1: the code diverges from your intent.</b> You cannot
        proofread your own mental model. The person who wrote the change is
        the person least able to see what it actually does, because they see
        what they meant. Copywriters institutionalized this truth a century
        before software: you can&rsquo;t proofread your own copy, because you
        read your intent, not your words. It&rsquo;s why every ad that
        mattered went through a copy chief, and why old-school proofreaders
        read <em>backwards</em> &mdash; breaking the sentence&rsquo;s
        meaning-template is the only way to make typos visible. A code
        reviewer is your copy chief: their entire power is that your intent
        isn&rsquo;t in their head. That&rsquo;s File 01, File 03, File 04
        &mdash; and the unsubscribe guard you may have missed fifteen
        paragraphs ago.
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>Channel 2: your intent diverges from the need.</b> You heard the
        request, built your interpretation, and the interpretation drifted
        &mdash; slightly at first, then compounding with every decision made
        alone. Code review is powerless here. The code is <em>correct</em>.
        It&rsquo;s correctly wrong. That&rsquo;s File 05 and File 06.
      </p>
      <p>
        One person cannot watch both channels, because both kinds of watching
        draw on the same budget that writing the code consumes. That&rsquo;s
        not a character flaw; that&rsquo;s the radiology result restated. The
        better you are at the primary task, the more completely the budget is
        spent on it.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 4 · The slowdown ============ -->
    <section id="slowdown">
      <p class="section-label">04 &middot; The bill</p>
      <h2>How blindness becomes slowness</h2>
      <p>
        Postmortems file these incidents under <em>quality</em>. The real bill
        is <em>speed</em>, and it compounds:
      </p>

      <figure class="diagram" role="img" aria-label="Diagram of the slowdown loop: a miss ships, is found late, triggers interrupt-driven rework, which raises work-in-progress and context switching, which raises attentional load, which produces more misses.">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 360" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="var(--font-mono)">
          <defs>
            <marker id="arr2" viewBox="0 0 10 10" refX="9" refY="5" markerWidth="7" markerHeight="7" orient="auto-start-reverse">
              <path d="M 0 1 L 9 5 L 0 9" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.6"/>
            </marker>
          </defs>
          <!-- 5 nodes around an ellipse, arrows clockwise -->
          <g font-size="12">
            <rect x="255" y="16" width="170" height="52" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="340" y="38" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-weight="500">a miss ships</text>
            <text x="340" y="56" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">(either channel)</text>

            <rect x="490" y="105" width="180" height="52" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="580" y="127" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-weight="500">found late</text>
            <text x="580" y="145" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">by a customer, not a test</text>

            <rect x="440" y="255" width="230" height="66" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="555" y="279" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-weight="500">interrupt-driven rework</text>
            <text x="555" y="297" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">incident channel &middot; damage audit</text>
            <text x="555" y="312" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">customer trust repair</text>

            <rect x="30" y="255" width="220" height="66" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="140" y="283" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-weight="500">WIP &amp; context-switching rise</text>
            <text x="140" y="301" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">the roadmap waits</text>

            <rect x="15" y="105" width="185" height="52" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
            <text x="107" y="127" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-weight="500">attentional load rises</text>
            <text x="107" y="145" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-terracotta)" font-size="11">blindness increases</text>
          </g>
          <path d="M 428 60 Q 520 70 566 100" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
          <path d="M 585 160 Q 600 210 575 250" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
          <path d="M 436 290 Q 345 305 256 289" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
          <path d="M 120 250 Q 95 210 105 162" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
          <path d="M 130 100 Q 175 55 250 42" fill="none" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.6" marker-end="url(#arr2)"/>
        </svg>
      </figure>

      <p>
        Walk the loop with a real one. The vendor-switch miss at Orai (File
        07) cost a fix measured in hours &mdash; handle one missing field.
        Everything <em>around</em> the fix was measured in weeks: the cluster
        of angry reviews, the support queue, the users who&rsquo;d been given
        nonsense feedback and had to be won back. All of it interrupt-driven,
        all of it fragmenting the team&rsquo;s attention, all of it raising
        the load that manufactures the next miss. And here&rsquo;s the detail
        that should sting: reviewing one batch of these files, <b>three out of
        four were fixed in under a day or two</b> once someone actually
        looked. The cost of a blind spot is never the fix. It&rsquo;s the
        months nobody was positioned to look.
      </p>
      <p>
        This is why startups slow down while everyone works harder. Velocity
        doesn&rsquo;t die in big dramatic failures. It bleeds out through
        rework loops that each looked like a one-off &mdash; each
        &ldquo;impossible to predict,&rdquo; each in plain sight of somebody
        who wasn&rsquo;t positioned to look. The classic industry estimate is
        that avoidable rework eats <b>40&ndash;50% of total project
        effort</b><sup><a href="#src-6">6</a></sup> &mdash; on a ten-person
        team, that&rsquo;s four or five salaries spent re-doing work nobody
        caught the first time. An engineer I trust frames it as literal
        finance: attention debt has a principal and an interest rate, and
        every rework loop is <em>interest due</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        And early-stage teams are structurally the blindest, because the
        things that make startups fast are the things that maximize
        attentional load: <b>solo ownership</b> (one pair of eyes per system;
        zero attention redundancy), <b>brutal context switching</b>, <b>demo-path
        pressure</b> (the Friday demo aims everyone&rsquo;s budget at the same
        pixels), and <b>no institutional memory</b> of past gorillas.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 5 · The triad ============ -->
    <section id="triad">
      <p class="section-label">05 &middot; The fix</p>
      <h2>One developer, two watchers</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        Here is the conclusion a decade of case files pushed me to &mdash; at
        Orai, again at CopyCat, and again now: <b>a developer is
        high-performance only inside a triangle</b> &mdash; a technical peer
        who keeps the code honest, and a non-technical standard holder who
        keeps the work aimed.
      </p>

      <figure class="diagram" role="img" aria-label="Triangle diagram: a developer supported by a technical peer watching channel 1 (technical misses) and a standard holder watching channel 2 (alignment misses).">
        <svg viewBox="0 0 680 330" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="var(--font-mono)">
          <!-- triangle edges -->
          <line x1="340" y1="66" x2="150" y2="240" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="340" y1="66" x2="530" y2="240" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <line x1="150" y1="240" x2="530" y2="240" stroke="var(--color-fog)" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="5 5"/>
          <!-- developer -->
          <rect x="255" y="18" width="170" height="56" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-ink-soft)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="340" y="42" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="13.5" font-weight="500">the developer</text>
          <text x="340" y="61" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="11">budget spent on building</text>
          <!-- peer -->
          <rect x="40" y="240" width="230" height="72" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-terracotta)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="155" y="264" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-terracotta)" font-size="11" letter-spacing="1.5">TECHNICAL PEER</text>
          <text x="155" y="284" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="12">&ldquo;what does this change</text>
          <text x="155" y="300" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="12">that you didn&rsquo;t intend?&rdquo;</text>
          <!-- standard holder -->
          <rect x="410" y="240" width="240" height="72" rx="10" fill="var(--color-cream-soft)" stroke="var(--color-sage-dim)" stroke-width="1.5"/>
          <text x="530" y="264" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-sage-dim)" font-size="11" letter-spacing="1.5">STANDARD HOLDER</text>
          <text x="530" y="284" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="12">&ldquo;is this the thing</text>
          <text x="530" y="300" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-ink)" font-size="12">we actually needed?&rdquo;</text>
          <!-- channel tags beside the edges -->
          <rect x="52" y="152" width="158" height="40" rx="10" fill="var(--color-terracotta)" opacity="0.12"/>
          <text x="131" y="169" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-terracotta)" font-size="10.5">covers channel 1</text>
          <text x="131" y="184" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="10.5">review &middot; pairing</text>
          <rect x="470" y="152" width="170" height="40" rx="10" fill="var(--color-sage-dim)" opacity="0.14"/>
          <text x="555" y="169" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-sage-dim)" font-size="10.5">covers channel 2</text>
          <text x="555" y="184" text-anchor="middle" fill="var(--color-stone)" font-size="10.5">demos &middot; definition of done</text>
        </svg>
      </figure>

      <p>
        <b>The technical peer</b> reviews with a different question than
        &ldquo;is this good code?&rdquo; Their question is: <em>what does this
        change do that you didn&rsquo;t intend?</em> They bring a fresh
        attention budget to your diff &mdash; they see the deleted guard
        clause while you&rsquo;re checking the rename, the ten-minute
        assumption while you&rsquo;re admiring the retry logic. Decades of
        inspection research say the same thing the gorilla lab does: a second,
        independent reader finds defects the author structurally
        cannot.<sup><a href="#src-5">5</a></sup> And because attention is a
        budget for the reviewer too, the best industrial data comes with a
        speed limit: past roughly 400 lines an hour, review defect-detection
        collapses.<sup><a href="#src-5">5</a></sup> A skimmed review is a
        gorilla video on fast-forward. And the payoff compounds: at one
        company I&rsquo;ve watched, an engineer publicly called the
        team&rsquo;s best reviewer &ldquo;the single largest multiplier to my
        personal productivity.&rdquo; Reviews don&rsquo;t demo well. They
        compound.
      </p>
      <p class="aside">
        Worried the second set of eyes slows you down? The radiology study has
        a detail for you: the radiologists who <em>did</em> spot the gorilla
        performed no worse at finding nodules.<sup><a href="#src-2">2</a></sup>
        Catching the anomaly and doing the primary job aren&rsquo;t in tension
        &mdash; they&rsquo;re only in tension when one person under load is
        trying to do both alone. (A fair heckle from a reviewer of this
        draft: &ldquo;yeah, but how much slower?&rdquo; The study didn&rsquo;t
        clock them &mdash; but the review-speed data above says slower
        <em>is</em> the point.)
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>The non-technical standard holder</b> &mdash; a PM, an ops lead, a
        domain expert, a founder &mdash; never reads the diff, and that is
        precisely their power. <em>They aren&rsquo;t hunting nodules, so they
        see gorillas instantly.</em> They look at the invoice, not the
        invoice-generation code &mdash; which is why, in the case files above,
        the person who finally saw the miss was so often outside engineering
        entirely. Their question &mdash;
        <em>is this the thing we needed?</em> &mdash; has to be asked early
        and repeatedly, not at the end. They hold the standard: what done
        means, what correct means, and whose definition of correct wins when
        two departments disagree (File 05 is entirely the absence of this
        person).
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>And this is the engineering case for diverse teams</b> &mdash; not
        the values-poster version, the velocity version. Homogeneous teams
        don&rsquo;t fail randomly; they fail <em>identically</em>. The
        radiologists didn&rsquo;t miss twenty different things &mdash; twenty
        of them missed the <em>same</em> gorilla, because they had all been
        trained onto the same template. AI shipped the most public
        demonstration of this in years: commercial facial-analysis systems
        that misclassified darker-skinned women at error rates up to
        <b>34.7%</b> while lighter-skinned men sat under 1% &mdash; trained on
        benchmarks that were roughly four-fifths lighter-skinned faces, built
        and tested by teams who never noticed, and caught by an MIT grad
        student the systems kept failing on.<sup><a href="#src-8">8</a></sup>
        That&rsquo;s a case file from this essay at industry scale: the
        gorilla was invisible to everyone whose face the demo path matched.
        Fresh eyes aren&rsquo;t a perk of diversity; they&rsquo;re the
        mechanism. Different backgrounds run different attention templates
        &mdash; it&rsquo;s why Fei-Fei Li built AI4ALL on the question
        &ldquo;AI will change the world. Who will change AI?&rdquo; A team
        that all looks, trains, and thinks alike is one attention system with
        extra keyboards.
      </p>
      <p>
        Notice what this is not. It is not &ldquo;add process.&rdquo;
        It&rsquo;s two relationships. And it lines up with one of the oldest
        findings in software engineering &mdash; that enormous slice of
        effort lost to avoidable rework is dominated by work that was aimed
        wrong before review could ever see it<sup><a href="#src-6">6</a></sup>
        &mdash; and one of the newest from the attention lab: no individual,
        however senior, can inspect their own blind spot. You don&rsquo;t fix
        attention with talent. You fix it with <em>coverage</em>.
      </p>

      <h3>What it looks like when it works</h3>
      <p>
        None of this requires a reorg. Across three companies I&rsquo;ve
        watched the triangle get recast per problem, not per title. At Orai I
        sat the non-technical corner as COO while a developer built and our
        CTO reviewed &mdash; and on other problems I flipped to the technical
        corner while our CEO held the standard.
        Designer&ndash;developer&ndash;CTO. Designer&ndash;developer&ndash;peer.
        PM&ndash;developer&ndash;tech-lead. At CopyCat,
        founder&ndash;developer&ndash;designer. The triangle is a pattern, not
        an org chart: one builder, one fresh technical eye, one keeper of what
        done means.
      </p>
      <p>
        And when the triangle is actually running, the numbers move. At Orai,
        the loop that mattered ran designer &rarr; developer &rarr; founder,
        week after week, on the first lesson a new user ever saw. As best I
        can reconstruct it &mdash; our old archives back the starting floor
        &mdash; completion of that first lesson went from <b>roughly one user
        in ten to well over half</b>. Nothing about the speech technology
        changed. What changed was three kinds of attention pointed at the
        same screen.
      </p>
      <p>
        At CopyCat, a manual audit in late 2022 put our component-detection
        accuracy between <b>29% and 75%</b> depending on element type &mdash;
        a coin flip on a good day. The loop was a PM running structured tests
        as standard holder, two ML engineers fixing, a founder reviewing. Two
        weeks later, the same tester&rsquo;s verdict on the new model:
        &ldquo;in a different league,&rdquo; false positives &ldquo;near
        absent.&rdquo; Months later, on the next iteration: &ldquo;exactly
        what we need.&rdquo; No hero. A measurement, a fix, and a standard
        holder who kept measuring.
      </p>
      <p>
        And recently, at a company I&rsquo;ll keep anonymous: an
        engineer&rsquo;s first week. Day one, joined. Day two, sat with the
        ops team and heard them complain about one screen. Days three and
        four, fixed it. Day five, the ops lead discovered the fix live,
        mid-demo. The same ops team later called a bigger rebuild of their
        console a total game-changer &mdash; their daily usage visibly
        steering what got built next. Pointed outward, the same pattern once
        produced a customer writing in unprompted: &ldquo;oh wow &mdash; that
        is easy.&rdquo;
      </p>
      <p>
        That is what traversing uncertainty pre-process looks like: the
        standard holder holds the moving target, the peer holds correctness,
        the builder builds &mdash; and the numbers move.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 6 · The automation objection ============ -->
    <section id="automation">
      <p class="section-label">06 &middot; The objection</p>
      <h2>&ldquo;Shouldn&rsquo;t a machine be watching this?&rdquo;</h2>
      <p class="lede">
        The sharpest response to a draft of this essay came from an engineer
        I trust, and it deserves to be answered at full strength.
      </p>
      <p>
        His argument: this is a very human-centric post, and the problem is
        bigger than any team&rsquo;s attention. Some systems are already too
        large for any owner&rsquo;s awareness &mdash; which is why mature
        industries stopped relying on awareness. Your car diagnoses itself
        over a bus protocol; no mechanic &ldquo;pays more attention&rdquo; to
        find the fault. Manufacturing didn&rsquo;t fix human error by hiring
        more careful humans; it built Jidoka, andon cords,
        pointing-and-calling. Humans are inherently non-deterministic &mdash;
        <em>today I pay attention, tomorrow I don&rsquo;t</em>. In his words,
        the structure I&rsquo;m proposing here is &ldquo;a sliver along a
        mountain of automations that is required.&rdquo;
      </p>
      <p>
        And he&rsquo;s right &mdash; embarrassingly, case by case. Walk the
        files back through his eyes: the vanished pricing rules (File 01) die
        under an acceptance test. The silent pipeline (File 02) dies under
        anomaly alerts. The logged-out crash (File 03): one end-to-end test.
        The trailing space (File 04): a linter. The vendor switch (File 07):
        contract tests on the response shape. <b>Every gorilla in this essay
        has a cage a machine could build.</b>
      </p>
      <p>
        So why isn&rsquo;t the essay titled &ldquo;write more tests&rdquo;?
        Because of the thing I left out of the first draft &mdash; ironic, in
        an essay about the things we leave out. <b>Startups are
        pre-process.</b> You own none of that mountain on day 30, and
        you&rsquo;re still expected to deliver like you have six-sigma
        energy. Worse: before product&ndash;market fit, <em>correct itself is
        still moving</em>. Half the checks you&rsquo;d lovingly write today
        would guard a building you&rsquo;re about to tear down. Channel 2
        doesn&rsquo;t just evade tests &mdash; it invalidates them. You
        cannot test your way out of not yet knowing what true means.
      </p>
      <p>
        And the triangle is not a consolation prize while you wait for real
        infrastructure. The fastest delivery I&rsquo;ve watched recently was
        triad-shaped precisely <em>because</em> there was no process to lean
        on: a cross-cutting migration everyone had kicked down the road for
        months &mdash; tentacles all over the most complex code, many ways to
        do it wrong &mdash; shipped in <b>nine working days instead of the
        month it &ldquo;should&rdquo; have taken</b>. Two developers, a
        reviewer who knew where the tentacles were, and a hard deadline held
        by the business side. Coverage made it fast, not slow.
      </p>
      <p>
        The deeper answer is that <b>automation is crystallized
        attention</b>. Every one of those cages had to be imagined by a
        person first. A test is a falsifiable hypothesis about your own code
        &mdash; the question my reviewer asks, and most of us are too proud
        to ask, is <em>&ldquo;what should be true for this to
        fail?&rdquo;</em> Someone has to see the failure mode before anyone
        can encode it. Tests guard the paths you&rsquo;ve already imagined;
        fresh attention is how you find the ones you haven&rsquo;t.
        That&rsquo;s not humans versus machines &mdash; it&rsquo;s an
        assembly line with two stations, and the human one is upstream.
      </p>
      <p>
        Which is what the triad actually produces, beyond caught bugs:
        <em>hypotheses worth encoding</em>. Run the root-cause ritual
        honestly &mdash; what were we staring at, who was positioned to see
        it? &mdash; and every answer that ends in &ldquo;a machine could
        watch this&rdquo; becomes this sprint&rsquo;s test or alert. That is
        the whole path from pre-process to process: <b>the triangle
        isn&rsquo;t the alternative to the automation mountain. It&rsquo;s
        the quarry.</b> Relentless alignment emits process as a byproduct.
        Pointing-and-calling was a human ritual long before it was a system;
        the ritual is how anyone learned what to systematize.
      </p>
      <p>
        My reviewer put a name on all of this that engineering education
        mostly skips: Karl Popper. Doctors get philosophy early, because it
        directly affects their patients; engineers are presumed to
        &ldquo;work with things,&rdquo; so we pick up falsifiability on the
        job or never. But software is a knowledge discipline wearing a hard
        hat. The reason we don&rsquo;t write falsification tests is the same
        reason we miss the gorilla: we are blind to our blindness &mdash;
        and being honest about that is where every real process, human or
        machine, begins.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 7 · Relentless alignment ============ -->
    <section id="practice">
      <p class="section-label">07 &middot; The practice</p>
      <h2>Relentless alignment</h2>
      <p>
        The triangle only works if contact is frequent. Alignment is not a
        kickoff meeting &mdash; it decays under load like everything else. The
        teams I&rsquo;ve watched stay fast treat it as a rhythm of small,
        boring, cheap corrections. Steal this:
      </p>

      <div class="checklist" id="ritualChecklist">
        <label class="ritual"><input type="checkbox" data-key="done-paragraph" />
          <span><b>Write what &ldquo;done&rdquo; means &mdash; one paragraph, before code.</b> The standard holder edits it. Ten minutes. Kills most alignment drift at birth.</span>
        </label>
        <label class="ritual"><input type="checkbox" data-key="ugly-demo" />
          <span><b>Show the ugly version at 30%.</b> Mid-flight demos on the real thing, not slides. AI tooling has made this nearly free &mdash; a rough-but-working version now costs hours, not days &mdash; so there&rsquo;s no excuse left. Drift caught at 30% costs a conversation; at 100% it costs a rewrite.</span>
        </label>
        <label class="ritual"><input type="checkbox" data-key="unintended-review" />
          <span><b>Review for the unintended, not just the incorrect.</b> Make &ldquo;what else does this change?&rdquo; a standing review question &mdash; and its falsification twin, &ldquo;what should be true for this to fail?&rdquo; Diffs lie by omission.</span>
        </label>
        <label class="ritual"><input type="checkbox" data-key="absence-alerts" />
          <span><b>Alert on absence, not just errors &mdash; and on surprising presence.</b> Silence is a failure mode; so is a number where none should be. If data stops arriving, or starts arriving where it shouldn&rsquo;t, something should scream (File 02).</span>
        </label>
        <label class="ritual"><input type="checkbox" data-key="attention-rca" />
          <span><b>Root-cause with the attention question.</b> Not &ldquo;who missed it?&rdquo; but &ldquo;what were we staring at when we missed it &mdash; and who was positioned to see it?&rdquo; Then fix the positioning, not the person.</span>
        </label>
        <label class="ritual"><input type="checkbox" data-key="fix-pattern" />
          <span><b>Fix the pattern, not the instance.</b> When a blind spot bites once, ask where else the same assumption lives &mdash; before it bites there too.</span>
        </label>
        <button type="button" class="copy-btn" id="copyChecklist">Copy as markdown</button>
      </div>

      <p>
        Each of these costs minutes. That&rsquo;s the point: a correction
        caught in a demo costs a conversation, while the same miss caught by a
        customer costs an incident &mdash; and, as the loop above shows, the
        next incident too. Relentless doesn&rsquo;t mean intense. It means
        <em>frequent</em> &mdash; the way a helmsman steers: tiny corrections,
        constantly, because the alternative isn&rsquo;t a straight line,
        it&rsquo;s arriving at the wrong port.
      </p>
    </section>

    <hr class="hairline" />

    <!-- ============ 8 · Close ============ -->
    <section id="close">
      <p class="section-label">08 &middot; The point</p>
      <h2>You can&rsquo;t out-focus blindness</h2>
      <p>
        Focus is not the cure for inattentional blindness. Focus is the
        <em>cause</em>. Effort spends the same budget; caring spends the same
        budget; seniority just spends it more efficiently on the primary task.
        The only fix that survives contact with a real sprint is structural:
        <b>more than one attention system, pointed at different questions,
        re-synced relentlessly.</b>
      </p>
      <p>
        One developer, plus a technical peer who catches the code diverging
        from intent, plus a non-technical standard holder who catches intent
        diverging from need. That&rsquo;s not overhead. Measured against the
        rework loop, it&rsquo;s the fastest configuration I&rsquo;ve seen in
        ten years of startups.
      </p>
      <p>
        The gorilla is already in your codebase. It&rsquo;s in mine. The only
        question is whether anyone on your team is positioned to see it &mdash;
        or whether your customers are your standard holders now.
      </p>
      <p class="cta">
        If this matches your experience &mdash; or you have the counterexample
        &mdash; I genuinely want to hear it.
      </p>

